# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chemistry/1-2-dioxetanedione] The chemical compound **1,2-dioxetanedione**, or **1,2-dioxacyclobutane-3,4-dione**, often called **peroxyacid ester**, is an unstable oxide of carbon (an oxocarbon) with formula C2O4.
[src:chemistry/1-2-dioxetanedione] It can be viewed as a double ketone of 1,2-dioxetane (1,2-dioxacyclobutane), or a cyclic dimer of carbon dioxide.
[src:chemistry/1-2-dioxetanedione] In ordinary conditions, it quickly decomposes to carbon dioxide (CO2) even at 180 K (−93.1 °C), but can be detected by mass spectrometry and other techniques.
[src:chemistry/1-2-dioxetanedione] 1,2-Dioxetanedione is an intermediate in the chemoluminescent reactions used in glowsticks.
[src:chemistry/1-2-dioxetanedione] The decomposition proceeds via a paramagnetic oxalate biradical intermediate.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni was well versed in physics, mathematics, astronomy, and natural sciences; he also distinguished himself as a historian, chronologist, and linguist.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He studied almost all the sciences of his day and was rewarded abundantly for his research in many fields of knowledge.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Royalty and other powerful elements in society funded al-Biruni's research and sought him out with specific projects in mind.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Influential in his own right, al-Biruni was himself influenced by the scholars of other nations, such as the Greeks, from whom he took inspiration when he turned to the study of philosophy.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] A gifted linguist, he was conversant in Khwarezmian, Persian, Arabic, and Sanskrit, and also knew Greek, Hebrew, and Syriac.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He spent much of his life in Ghazni, then capital of the Ghaznavids, in modern-day central-eastern Afghanistan.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In 1017, he travelled to the Indian subcontinent and wrote a treatise on Indian culture entitled *Tārīkh al-Hind* ("*The History of India*"), after exploring the Hindu faith practiced in India.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He was, for his time, an admirably impartial writer on the customs and creeds of various nations, his scholarly objectivity earning him the title *al-Ustadh* ("The Master") in recognition of his remarkable description of early 11th-century India.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni's name is derived from the Persian word *bērūn* or *bīrūn* ("outskirts"), as he was born in an outlying district of Kath, the capital of the Afrighid kingdom of Khwarazm.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The city, now called Beruniy, is part of the autonomous republic of Karakalpakstan in northwest Uzbekistan.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] His name was most commonly latinized as *Alberonius*.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni spent the first twenty-five years of his life in Khwarezm where he studied Islamic jurisprudence, theology, grammar, mathematics, astronomy, medicine and philosophy and dabbled not only in the field of physics, but also in those of most of the other sciences.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He was sympathetic to the Afrighids, who were overthrown by the rival dynasty of Ma'munids in 995.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He left his homeland for Bukhara, then under the Samanid ruler Mansur II the son of Nuh II.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He corresponded with Avicenna, and there are extant exchanges of views between these two scholars.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In 998, he went to the court of the Ziyarid amir of Tabaristan, Qabus (r.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He also visited the court of the Bavandid ruler Al-Marzuban.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Accepting the definite demise of the Afrighids at the hands of the Ma'munids, he made peace with the latter who then ruled Khwarezm.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Their court at Gorganj (also in Khwarezm) was gaining fame for its gathering of brilliant scientists.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Most scholars, including al-Biruni, were taken to Ghazni, the capital of the Ghaznavid dynasty.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni was made court astrologer and accompanied Mahmud on his invasions into India, living there for a few years.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He was 44 when he went on the journeys with Mahmud of Ghazni.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni became acquainted with all things related to India.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] During this time he wrote his study of India, finishing it around 1030.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Along with his writing, Al-Biruni also made sure to extend his study to sciences while on the expeditions.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He sought to find a method to measure the height of the sun, and created a makeshift quadrant for that purpose.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni was able to make much progress in his study over the frequent travels that he went on throughout the lands of India.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Of the 146 books written by al-Bīrūnī, 95 are devoted to astronomy, mathematics, and related subjects like mathematical geography.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In carrying out his research, al-Biruni used a variety of different techniques dependent upon the particular field of study involved.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In a later work, he wrote a refutation of astrology, in contradistinction to the legitimate science of astronomy, for which he expresses wholehearted support.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Some suggest that his reasons for refuting astrology relate to the methods used by astrologers being based upon pseudoscience rather than empiricism and also to a conflict between the views of the astrologers and those of the orthodox theologians of Sunni Islam.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In his major astronomical work, the *Mas'ud Canon*, Biruni observed that, contrary to Ptolemy, the Sun's apogee (highest point in the heavens) was mobile, not fixed.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He wrote a treatise on the astrolabe, describing how to use it to tell the time and as a quadrant for surveying.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] One particular diagram of an eight-geared device could be considered an ancestor of later Muslim astrolabes and clocks.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] More recently, Biruni's eclipse data was used by Dunthorne in 1749 to help determine the acceleration of the Moon, and his data on equinox times and eclipses was used as part of a study of Earth's past rotation.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He further stated that Aristotle, whose arguments Avicenna uses, contradicted himself when he stated that the universe and matter has a start whilst holding on to the idea that matter is pre-eternal.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In his letters to Avicenna, he stated the argument of Aristotle, that there is a change in the creator.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni was proud of the fact that he followed the textual evidence of the religion without being influenced by Greek philosophers such as Aristotle.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni contributed to the introduction of the scientific method to medieval mechanics.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He developed experimental methods to determine density, using a particular type of hydrostatic balance.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni's method of using the hydrostatic balance was precise, and he was able to measure the density of many different substances, including precious metals, gems, and even air.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He also used an experimental method to determine the radius of the earth, which he did by measuring the angle of elevation of the horizon from the top of a mountain and comparing it to the angle of elevation of the horizon from a nearby plain.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In addition to developing the hydrostatic balance, Al-Biruni also wrote extensively on the topic of density, including the different types of densities and how they are measured.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] His work on the subject was very influential.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Bīrūnī devised a novel method of determining the Earth's radius by means of the observation of the height of a mountain.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He carried it out at Nandana in Pind Dadan Khan (present-day Pakistan).
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He used trigonometry to calculate the radius of the Earth using measurements of the height of a hill and measurement of the dip in the horizon from the top of that hill.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Sparavigna writes that his calculated radius for the Earth of 3928.77 miles was 2% higher than the actual mean radius of 3847.80 miles.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] His estimate was given as 12,803,337 cubits, so the accuracy of his estimate compared to the modern value depends on what conversion is used for cubits.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The exact length of a cubit is not clear; with an 18-inch cubit his estimate would be 3,600 miles, whereas with a 22-inch cubit his estimate would be 4,200 miles.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] One significant problem with this approach is that Al-Biruni was not aware of atmospheric refraction and made no allowance for it.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He used a dip angle of 34 arc minutes in his calculations, but refraction can typically alter the measured dip angle by about 1/6, making his calculation only accurate to within about 20% of the true value.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In his *Codex Masudicus* (1037), Al-Biruni theorized the existence of a landmass along the vast ocean between Asia and Europe, or what is today known as the Americas.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He also theorized that at least some of the unknown landmass would lie within the known latitudes which humans could inhabit, and therefore would be inhabited.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni wrote a pharmacopoeia, the *Kitab al-saydala fi al-tibb* ("*Book on the Pharmacopoeia of Medicine*").
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] It lists synonyms for drug names in Syriac, Persian, Greek, Baluchi, Afghan, Kurdish, and some Indian languages.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He used a hydrostatic balance to determine the density and purity of metals and precious stones.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He classified gems by what he considered their primary physical properties, such as specific gravity and hardness, rather than the common practice of the time of classifying them by colour.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni's main essay on political history, *Kitāb al-musāmara fī aḵbār Ḵᵛārazm* ("*Book of nightly conversation concerning the affairs of Ḵᵛārazm*") is now known only from quotations in Bayhaqī's Tārīkh-e Masʿūdī.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In addition to this various discussions of historical events and methodology are found in connection with the lists of kings in his al-Āthār al-bāqiya and in the Qānūn as well as elsewhere in the Āthār, in India, and scattered throughout his other works.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni's *Chronology of Ancient Nations* attempted to accurately establish the length of various historical eras.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni is widely considered to be one of the most important Muslim authorities on the history of religion.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He is known as a pioneer in the field of comparative religion in his study of, among other creeds, Zoroastrianism, Judaism, Hinduism, Christianity, Buddhism and Islam.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He strove to understand them on their own terms rather than trying to prove them wrong.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] His underlying concept was that all cultures are at least distant relatives of all other cultures because they are all human constructs.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni divides Hindus into an educated and an uneducated class.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He describes the educated as monotheistic, believing that God is one, eternal, and omnipotent and eschewing all forms of idol worship.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He recognizes that uneducated Hindus worshiped a multiplicity of idols yet points out that even some Muslims (such as the Jabriyah) have adopted anthropomorphic concepts of God.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni wrote about the peoples, customs and religions of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Ahmed, like modern anthropologists, he engaged in extensive participant observation with a given group of people, learnt their language and studied their primary texts, presenting his findings with objectivity and neutrality using cross-cultural comparisons.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Ahmed concluded that Al-Biruni can be considered as the first anthropologist, others, however, have argued that he can hardly be considered an anthropologist in the conventional sense.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni's fame as an Indologist rests primarily on two texts.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] During his journey through India, military and political history were not Biruni's main focus: he decided rather to document the civilian and scholarly aspects of Hindu life, examining culture, science, and religion.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He explored religion within a rich cultural context.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] An example of Biruni's analysis is his summary of why many Hindus hate Muslims.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni notes in the beginning of his book how the Muslims had a hard time learning about Hindu knowledge and culture.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He explains that Hinduism and Islam are totally different from each other.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Moreover, Hindus in 11th century India had suffered waves of destructive attacks on many of its cities, and Islamic armies had taken numerous Hindu slaves to Persia, which – claimed Biruni – contributed to Hindus becoming suspicious of all foreigners, not just Muslims.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Hindus considered Muslims violent and impure, and did not want to share anything with them.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Over time, Biruni won the welcome of Hindu scholars.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni collected books and studied with these Hindu scholars to become fluent in Sanskrit, discover and translate into Arabic the mathematics, science, medicine, astronomy and other fields of arts as practiced in 11th-century India.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He was inspired by the arguments offered by Indian scholars who believed earth must be globular in shape, which they felt was the only way to fully explain the difference in daylight hours by latitude, seasons and Earth's relative positions with Moon and stars.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] At the same time, Biruni was also critical of Indian scribes, who he believed carelessly corrupted Indian documents while making copies of older documents.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He also criticized the Hindus on what he saw them do and not do, for example finding them deficient in curiosity about history and religion.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] One of the specific aspects of Hindu life that Biruni studied was the Hindu calendar.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] His scholarship on the topic exhibited great determination and focus, not to mention the excellence in his approach of the in-depth research he performed.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He developed a method for converting the dates of the Hindu calendar to the dates of the three different calendars that were common in the Islamic countries of his time period, the Greek, the Arab/Muslim, and the Persian.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni also employed astronomy in the determination of his theories, which were complex mathematical equations and scientific calculations that allows one to convert dates and years between the different calendars.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The book does not limit itself to tedious records of battle because Biruni found the social culture to be more important.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The work includes research on a vast array of topics of Indian culture, including descriptions of their traditions and customs.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Although he tried to stay away from political and military history, Biruni did indeed record important dates and noted actual sites of where significant battles occurred.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Additionally, he chronicled stories of Indian rulers and told of how they ruled over their people with their beneficial actions and acted in the interests of the nation.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] His details are brief and mostly just list rulers without referring to their real names, and he did not go on about deeds that each one carried out during their reign, which keeps in line with Biruni's mission to try to stay away from political histories.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni also described the geography of India in his work.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He documented different bodies of water and other natural phenomena.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] These descriptions are useful to today's modern historians because they are able to use Biruni's scholarship to locate certain destinations in modern-day India.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Historians are able to make some matches while also concluding that certain areas seem to have disappeared and been replaced with different cities.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Different forts and landmarks were able to be located, legitimizing Biruni's contributions with their usefulness to even modern history and archeology.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The dispassionate account of Hinduism given by Biruni was remarkable for its time.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He stated that he was fully objective in his writings, remaining unbiased like a proper historian should.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni documented everything about India just as it happened.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] But, he did note how some of the accounts of information that he was given by natives of the land may not have been reliable in terms of complete accuracy, however, he did try to be as honest as possible in his writing.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Eduard Sachau compares it to "a magic island of quiet, impartial research in the midst of a world of clashing swords, burning towns, and plundered temples." Biruni's writing was very poetic, which may diminish some of the historical value of the work for modern times.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The lack of description of battle and politics makes those parts of the picture completely lost.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] However, many have used Biruni's work to check facts of history in other works that may have been ambiguous or had their validity questioned.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni, as a Muslim critical thinker, integrated in his studies between 'aql (reason) and naql (revelation).
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni did not say whether he was Sunni or Shia; rather, he only identified as a Muslim.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Fischel, Al-Biruni was "the greatest Muslim Hebraist".
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] According to Yasir Qadhi, Al-Biruni was "not pro-Hadith" and was "sceptical of the Hadith".
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni rejected hadiths which contradicted science.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] For example, his rejection of the fasting hadith on Ashura, which is reported in Sahih al-Bukhari, was based on historical and scientific reasoning, indicating a critical approach to hadith where he found contradictions with verifiable facts.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni used astronomical and historical calculations to argue that the 10th of Muharram (Ashura) could not have coincided with the Jewish day of Atonement (Yom Kippur, 10th of Tishri) in the second year of the Hijra, as suggested by some hadiths.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He noted that the dates could not have fallen on the same day, thus the premise of the hadith that the prophet Muhammad fasted because the Jews did was historically and astronomically flawed.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni counted as "caliphs" Abu Bakr, Umar ibn al-Khattab, Uthman ibn Affan, Ali ibn Abi Talib, and Hasan ibn Ali; the Umayyads were designated as "kings", the Abbasids as "imams".
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni defended the Mu'tazilites against a slanderous misrepresentation of their doctrines.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Al-Biruni was as unequivocal in rejecting beliefs unacceptable to Muslims as he is in condemning unfair criticism of other faiths, such as Christianity.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Though he criticised the Trinity, he believed that the Tawrat and Injeel use the words "father" and "son" in a metaphorical, as well as a literal, sense.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Most of the works of Al-Biruni are in Arabic although he seemingly wrote the *Kitab al-Tafhim* in both Persian and Arabic, showing his mastery over both languages.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni wrote most of his works in Arabic, the scientific language of his age, but *al-Tafhim* is one of the most important of the early works of science in Persian, and is a rich source for Persian prose and lexicography.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The book covers the *Quadrivium* in a detailed and skilled fashion.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Following Al-Biruni's death, his work was neither built upon nor referenced by scholars.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Centuries later, his writings about India, which had become of interest to the British Raj, were revisited.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] The lunar crater Al-Biruni and the asteroid 9936 Al-Biruni are named in his honour.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Biruni Island in Antarctica is named after al-Biruni.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In Iran, surveying engineers are celebrated on al-Biruni's birthday.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] In June 2009, Iran donated a pavilion to the United Nations Office in Vienna—placed in the central Memorial Plaza of the Vienna International Center.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Named the Scholars Pavilion, it features the statues of four prominent Iranian scholars: Avicenna, Abu Rayhan Biruni, Zakariya Razi (Rhazes) and Omar Khayyam.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] A film about the life of Al-Biruni, *Abu Raykhan Beruni*, was released in the Soviet Union in 1974.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] Irrfan Khan portrayed Al-Biruni in the 1988 Doordarshan historical drama *Bharat Ek Khoj*.
[src:chemistry/abū-al-rayhān-al-bīrūnī] He has been portrayed by Cüneyt Uzunlar in the Turkish television series *Alparslan: Büyük Selçuklu* on TRT 1.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In chemistry, an **acid–base reaction** is a chemical reaction that occurs between an acid and a base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It can be used to determine pH via titration.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Several theoretical frameworks provide alternative conceptions of the reaction mechanisms and their application in solving related problems; these are called the acid–base theories, for example, Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Their importance becomes apparent in analyzing acid–base reactions for gaseous or liquid species, or when acid or base character may be somewhat less apparent.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The first of these concepts was provided by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, around 1776.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It is important to think of the acid–base reaction models as theories that complement each other.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] For example, the current Lewis model has the broadest definition of what an acid and base are, with the Brønsted–Lowry theory being a subset of what acids and bases are, and the Arrhenius theory being the most restrictive.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius theory describes an acid as a substance that increases the concentration of hydrogen ions (H3O+ or H+) in a solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A base is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] However, Arrhenius's definition only applies to substances that are in water.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The concept of an acid–base reaction was first proposed in 1754 by Guillaume-François Rouelle, who introduced the word "base" into chemistry to mean a substance which reacts with an acid to give it solid form (as a salt).
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The first scientific concept of acids and bases was provided by Lavoisier in around 1776.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Lavoisier definition held for over 30 years, until the 1810 article and subsequent lectures by Sir Humphry Davy in which he proved the lack of oxygen in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), hydrogen telluride (H2Te), and the hydrohalic acids.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] However, Davy failed to develop a new theory, concluding that "acidity does not depend upon any particular elementary substance, but upon peculiar arrangement of various substances".
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] One notable modification of oxygen theory was provided by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, who stated that acids are oxides of nonmetals while bases are oxides of metals.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In 1838, Justus von Liebig proposed that an acid is a hydrogen-containing compound whose hydrogen can be replaced by a metal.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This redefinition was based on his extensive work on the chemical composition of organic acids, finishing the doctrinal shift from oxygen-based acids to hydrogen-based acids started by Davy.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Liebig's definition, while completely empirical, remained in use for almost 50 years until the adoption of the Arrhenius definition.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The first modern definition of acids and bases in molecular terms was devised by Svante Arrhenius.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A hydrogen theory of acids, it followed from his 1884 work with Friedrich Wilhelm Ostwald in establishing the presence of ions in aqueous solution and led to Arrhenius receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This causes the protonation of water, or the creation of the hydronium (H3O+) ion.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in modern times, the symbol H+ is interpreted as a shorthand for H3O+, because it is now known that a bare proton does not exist as a free species in aqueous solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This is the species which is measured by pH indicators to measure the acidity or basicity of a solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius definitions of acidity and alkalinity are restricted to aqueous solutions and are not valid for most non-aqueous solutions, and refer to the concentration of the solvent ions.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Under this definition, pure H2SO4 and HCl dissolved in toluene are not acidic, and molten NaOH and solutions of calcium amide in liquid ammonia are not alkaline.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This led to the development of the Brønsted–Lowry theory and subsequent Lewis theory to account for these non-aqueous exceptions.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of an acid with a base is called a neutralization reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this traditional representation an acid–base neutralization reaction is formulated as a double-replacement reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The modifier (aq) in this equation was implied by Arrhenius, rather than included explicitly.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It indicates that the substances are dissolved in water.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Though all three substances, HCl, NaOH and NaCl are capable of existing as pure compounds, in aqueous solutions they are fully dissociated into the aquated ions H+, Cl−, Na+ and OH−.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is used to cause the dough for breads and cakes to "rise" by creating millions of tiny carbon dioxide bubbles.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is not to be confused with baking soda, which is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3).
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is a mixture of baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) and acidic salts.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The bubbles are created because, when the baking powder is combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Whether commercially or domestically prepared, the principles behind baking powder formulations remain the same.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The real reactions are more complicated because the acids are complicated.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A typical formulation (by weight) could call for 30% sodium bicarbonate, 5–12% monocalcium phosphate, and 21–26% sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Alternately, a commercial baking powder might use sodium acid pyrophosphate as one of the two acidic components instead of sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Another typical acid in such formulations is cream of tartar (KC4H5O6), a derivative of tartaric acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An acid–base reaction is, thus, the removal of a proton from the acid and its addition to the base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The removal of a proton from an acid produces its *conjugate base*, which is the acid with a proton removed.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reception of a proton by a base produces its *conjugate acid*, which is the base with a proton added.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Unlike the previous definitions, the Brønsted–Lowry definition does not refer to the formation of salt and solvent, but instead to the formation of *conjugate acids* and *conjugate bases*, produced by the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this approach, acids and bases are fundamentally different in behavior from salts, which are seen as electrolytes, subject to the theories of Debye, Onsager, and others.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An acid and a base react not to produce a salt and a solvent, but to form a new acid and a new base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The concept of neutralization is thus absent.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base behavior is formally independent of any solvent, making it more all-encompassing than the Arrhenius model.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The calculation of pH under the Arrhenius model depended on alkalis (bases) dissolving in water (aqueous solution).
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model expanded what could be pH tested using insoluble and soluble solutions (gas, liquid, solid).
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The general formula for acid–base reactions according to the Brønsted–Lowry definition is: ${\ce {HA + B -> BH+ + A-}}$ where HA represents the acid, B represents the base, BH+ represents the conjugate acid of B, and A− represents the conjugate base of HA.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The removal of H+ from the HCl produces the chloride ion, Cl−, the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The addition of H+ to the H2O (acting as a base) forms the hydronium ion, H3O+, the conjugate acid of the base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Water is amphoteric – that is, it can act as both an acid and a base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Here, one molecule of water acts as an acid, donating an H+ and forming the conjugate base, OH−, and a second molecule of water acts as a base, accepting the H+ ion and forming the conjugate acid, H3O+.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this example, a water molecule is split into a hydrogen cation, which is donated to a pyridine molecule, and a hydroxide ion.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In the Brønsted–Lowry model, the solvent does not necessarily have to be water, as is required by the Arrhenius Acid–Base model.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An H+ ion is removed from acetic acid, forming its conjugate base, the acetate ion, CH3COO−.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The addition of an H+ ion to an ammonia molecule of the solvent creates its conjugate acid, the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model calls hydrogen-containing substances (like HCl) acids.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus, some substances, which many chemists considered to be acids, such as SO3 or BCl3, are excluded from this classification due to lack of hydrogen.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The hydrogen requirement of Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry was removed by the Lewis definition of acid–base reactions, devised by Gilbert N.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Lewis in 1923, in the same year as Brønsted–Lowry, but it was not elaborated by him until 1938.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Instead of defining acid–base reactions in terms of protons or other bonded substances, the Lewis definition defines a base (referred to as a *Lewis base*) to be a compound that can donate an *electron pair*, and an acid (a *Lewis acid*) to be a compound that can receive this electron pair.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] For example, boron trifluoride, BF3 is a typical Lewis acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] It can accept a pair of electrons as it has a vacancy in its octet.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The fluoride ion has a full octet and can donate a pair of electrons.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus ${\ce {BF3 + F- -> BF4-}}$ is a typical Lewis acid, Lewis base reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] All compounds of group 13 elements with a formula AX3 can behave as Lewis acids.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Similarly, compounds of group 15 elements with a formula DY3, such as amines, NR3, and phosphines, PR3, can behave as Lewis bases.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Adducts between them have the formula X3A←DY3 with a dative covalent bond, shown symbolically as ←, between the atoms A (acceptor) and D (donor).
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Compounds of group 16 with a formula DX2 may also act as Lewis bases; in this way, a compound like an ether, R2O, or a thioether, R2S, can act as a Lewis base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis definition is not limited to these examples.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] For instance, carbon monoxide acts as a Lewis base when it forms an adduct with boron trifluoride, of formula F3B←CO.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Adducts involving metal ions are referred to as co-ordination compounds; each ligand donates a pair of electrons to the metal ion.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reaction ${\ce {[Ag(H2O)4]+ + 2 NH3 -> [Ag(NH3)2]+ + 4 H2O}}$ can be seen as an acid–base reaction in which a stronger base (ammonia) replaces a weaker one (water).
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are consistent with each other since the reaction ${\ce {H+ + OH- <=> H2O}}$ is an acid–base reaction in both theories.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] One of the limitations of the Arrhenius definition is its reliance on water solutions.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Edward Curtis Franklin studied the acid–base reactions in liquid ammonia in 1905 and pointed out the similarities to the water-based Arrhenius theory.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Germann, working with liquid phosgene, COCl 2, formulated the solvent-based theory in 1925, thereby generalizing the Arrhenius definition to cover aprotic solvents.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvonium ions and a decrease in the concentration of solvate ions is defined as an *acid*.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvate ions and a decrease in the concentration of the solvonium ions is defined as a *base*.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in liquid ammonia, KNH2 (supplying NH−2) is a strong base, and NH4NO3 (supplying NH+4) is a strong acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In liquid sulfur dioxide (SO2), thionyl compounds (supplying SO2+) behave as acids, and sulfites (supplying SO2−3) behave as bases.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] On the other hand, solvent system theory has been criticized as being too general to be useful.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Also, it has been thought that there is something intrinsically acidic about hydrogen compounds, a property not shared by non-hydrogenic solvonium salts.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This acid–base theory was a revival of the oxygen theory of acids and bases proposed by German chemist Hermann Lux in 1939, further improved by Håkon Flood c.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] 1947 and is still used in modern geochemistry and electrochemistry of molten salts.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This definition describes an acid as an oxide ion (O2−) acceptor and a base as an oxide ion donor.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This theory is also useful in the systematisation of the reactions of noble gas compounds, especially the xenon oxides, fluorides, and oxofluorides.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Mikhail Usanovich developed a general theory that does not restrict acidity to hydrogen-containing compounds, but his approach, published in 1938, was even more general than Lewis theory.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Usanovich's theory can be summarized as defining an acid as anything that accepts negative species or donates positive ones, and a base as the reverse.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This defined the concept of redox (oxidation-reduction) as a special case of acid–base reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In 1963, Ralph Pearson proposed a qualitative concept known as the Hard and Soft Acids and Bases principle. later made quantitative with help of Robert Parr in 1984.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] 'Hard' applies to species that are small, have high charge states, and are weakly polarizable.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] 'Soft' applies to species that are large, have low charge states and are strongly polarizable.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Acids and bases interact, and the most stable interactions are hard–hard and soft–soft.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] This theory has found use in organic and inorganic chemistry.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Drago is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The model assigned E and C parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Each acid is characterized by an *E*A and a *C*A.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Each base is likewise characterized by its own *E*B and *C*B.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The E and C parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The W term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The equation predicts reversal of acids and base strengths.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of a strong acid with a strong base is essentially a quantitative reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] In this reaction both the sodium and chloride ions are spectators as the neutralization reaction, ${\ce {H+ + OH- -> H2O}}$ does not involve them.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] With weak bases addition of acid is not quantitative because a solution of a weak base is a buffer solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] A solution of a weak acid is also a buffer solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] When a weak acid reacts with a weak base an equilibrium mixture is produced.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] The notation [X] signifies "concentration of X".
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] An acid–alkali reaction is a special case of an acid–base reaction, where the base used is also an alkali.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] When an acid reacts with an alkali salt (a metal hydroxide), the product is a metal salt and water.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Acid–alkali reactions are also neutralization reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Acids are in general pure substances that contain hydrogen cations (H+) or cause them to be produced in solutions.
[src:chemistry/acid-base-reaction] Hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4) are common examples.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:chemistry/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:chemistry/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:chemistry/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:chemistry/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:chemistry/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:chemistry/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:chemistry/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:chemistry/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:chemistry/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:chemistry/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:chemistry/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:chemistry/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:chemistry/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:chemistry/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:chemistry/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:chemistry/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:chemistry/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:chemistry/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:chemistry/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:chemistry/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:chemistry/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:chemistry/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:chemistry/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:chemistry/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:chemistry/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:chemistry/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:chemistry/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:chemistry/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:chemistry/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:chemistry/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:chemistry/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:chemistry/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:chemistry/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:chemistry/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:chemistry/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:chemistry/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:chemistry/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:chemistry/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:chemistry/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:chemistry/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:chemistry/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:chemistry/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:chemistry/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:chemistry/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:chemistry/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:chemistry/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:chemistry/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:chemistry/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:chemistry/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:chemistry/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:chemistry/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:chemistry/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:chemistry/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:chemistry/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:chemistry/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:chemistry/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:chemistry/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:chemistry/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:chemistry/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:chemistry/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:chemistry/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:chemistry/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:chemistry/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:chemistry/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:chemistry/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:chemistry/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:chemistry/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:chemistry/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:chemistry/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:chemistry/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:chemistry/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:chemistry/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:chemistry/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:chemistry/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:chemistry/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:chemistry/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:chemistry/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:chemistry/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:chemistry/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:chemistry/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:chemistry/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:chemistry/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:chemistry/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:chemistry/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:chemistry/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:chemistry/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:chemistry/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:chemistry/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:chemistry/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:chemistry/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:chemistry/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:chemistry/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:chemistry/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:chemistry/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:chemistry/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:chemistry/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:chemistry/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:chemistry/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:chemistry/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:chemistry/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:chemistry/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:chemistry/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:chemistry/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:chemistry/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:chemistry/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:chemistry/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:chemistry/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:chemistry/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:chemistry/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:chemistry/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:chemistry/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:chemistry/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:chemistry/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:chemistry/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:chemistry/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:chemistry/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:chemistry/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:chemistry/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:chemistry/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:chemistry/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:chemistry/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:chemistry/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:chemistry/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:chemistry/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:chemistry/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:chemistry/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:chemistry/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:chemistry/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:chemistry/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:chemistry/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:chemistry/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:chemistry/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:chemistry/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:chemistry/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:chemistry/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:chemistry/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:chemistry/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:chemistry/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:chemistry/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:chemistry/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:chemistry/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:chemistry/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:chemistry/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:chemistry/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:chemistry/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:chemistry/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:chemistry/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:chemistry/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:chemistry/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:chemistry/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:chemistry/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:chemistry/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:chemistry/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:chemistry/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:chemistry/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:chemistry/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:chemistry/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:chemistry/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:chemistry/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:chemistry/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:chemistry/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:chemistry/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:chemistry/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:chemistry/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:chemistry/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:chemistry/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:chemistry/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:chemistry/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:chemistry/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:chemistry/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:chemistry/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:chemistry/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:chemistry/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:chemistry/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:chemistry/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:chemistry/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:chemistry/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:chemistry/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:chemistry/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In contrast to the relatively early flowering of organotransition-metal chemistry (1955 to the present), the corresponding development of actinide organometallic chemistry has taken place largely within the past 15 or so years.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] During this period, 5f organometallic science has blossomed, and it is now apparent that the actinides have a rich, intricate, and highly informative organometallic chemistry.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Intriguing parallels to and sharp differences from the d-block elements have emerged.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Actinides can coordinate the organic active groups or bind to carbon by the covalent bonds.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The necessity of obtaining accurate thermodynamic quantities for the actinide elements and their compounds was recognized at the outset of the Manhattan Project, when a dedicated team of scientists and engineers initiated the program to exploit nuclear energy for military purposes.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Since the end of World War II, both fundamental and applied objectives have motivated a great deal of further study of actinide thermodynamics.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The possibility of using unique properties of lanthanides in the nanotechnology is demonstrated.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The origination of linear and nonlinear optical properties of lanthanide compounds with phthalocyanines, porphyrins, naphthalocyanines, and their analogs in solutions and condensed state and the prospects of obtaining novel materials on their basis are discussed.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Based on the electronic structure and properties of lanthanides and their compounds, namely, optical and magnetic characteristics, electronic and ionic conductivity, and fluctuating valence, molecular engines are classified.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] It is shown that thermodynamically stable nanoparticles of Ln*x*M*y* composition can be formed by d elements of the second halves of the series, i.e., those arranged after M = Mn, Tc, and Re.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Generally, ingested insoluble actinide compounds such as high-fired uranium dioxide and mixed oxide (MOX) fuel will pass through the digestive system with little effect since they cannot dissolve and be absorbed by the body.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Inhaled actinide compounds, however, will be more damaging as they remain in the lungs and irradiate the lung tissue.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Ingested Low-fired oxides and soluble salts such as nitrate can be absorbed into the blood stream.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] If they are inhaled then it is possible for the solid to dissolve and leave the lungs.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Hence the dose to the lungs will be lower for the soluble form.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Radon and radium are not actinides—they are both radioactive daughters from the decay of uranium.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Aspects of their biology and environmental behaviour is discussed at radium in the environment.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In India, a large amount of thorium ore can be found in the form of monazite in placer deposits of the Western and Eastern coastal dune sands, particularly in the Tamil Nadu coastal areas.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The residents of this area are exposed to a naturally occurring radiation dose ten times higher than the worldwide average.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Thorium has been linked to liver cancer.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In the past thoria (thorium dioxide) was used as a contrast agent for medical X-ray radiography but its use has been discontinued.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Uranium is about as abundant as arsenic or molybdenum.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Significant concentrations of uranium occur in some substances such as phosphate rock deposits, and minerals such as lignite, and monazite sands in uranium-rich ores (it is recovered commercially from these sources).
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Seawater contains about 3.3 parts per billion of uranium by weight as uranium(VI) forms soluble carbonate complexes.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The extraction of uranium from seawater has been considered as a means of obtaining the element.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Because of the very low specific activity of uranium the chemical effects of it upon living things can often outweigh the effects of its radioactivity.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Plutonium, like other actinides, readily forms a plutonium dioxide (*plutonyl*) core (PuO2).
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] In the environment, this plutonyl core readily complexes with carbonate as well as other oxygen moieties (OH−, NO− 2, NO− 3, and SO2− 4) to form charged complexes which can be readily mobile with low affinities to soil.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Some early evidence for nuclear fission was the formation of a short-lived radioisotope of barium which was isolated from neutron irradiated uranium (139Ba, with a half-life of 83 minutes and 140Ba, with a half-life of 12.8 days, are major fission products of uranium).
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] At the time, it was thought that this was a new radium isotope, as it was then standard radiochemical practice to use a barium sulfate carrier precipitate to assist in the isolation of radium.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The PUREX process is a liquid–liquid extraction ion-exchange method used to reprocess spent nuclear fuel, in order to extract primarily uranium and plutonium, independent of each other, from the other constituents.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The current method of choice is to use the PUREX liquid–liquid extraction process which uses a tributyl phosphate/hydrocarbon mixture to extract both uranium and plutonium from nitric acid.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] This extraction is of the nitrate salts and is classed as being of a solvation mechanism.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] For example, the extraction of plutonium by an extraction agent (S) in a nitrate medium occurs by the following reaction.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] A complex bond is formed between the metal cation, the nitrates and the tributyl phosphate, and a model compound of a dioxouranium(VI) complex with two nitrates and two triethyl phosphates has been characterised by X-ray crystallography.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] After the dissolution step it is normal to remove the fine insoluble solids, because otherwise they will disturb the solvent extraction process by altering the liquid-liquid interface.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] It is known that the presence of a fine solid can stabilize an emulsion.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Emulsions are often referred to as third phases in the solvent extraction community.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] An organic solvent composed of 30% tributyl phosphate (TBP) in a hydrocarbon solvent, such as kerosene, is used to extract the uranium as UO2(NO3)2·2TBP complexes, and plutonium as similar complexes, from other fission products, which remain in the aqueous phase.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The transuranium elements americium and curium also remain in the aqueous phase.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The nature of the organic soluble uranium complex has been the subject of some research.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] A series of complexes of uranium with nitrate and trialkyl phosphates and phosphine oxides have been characterized.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] Plutonium is separated from uranium by treating the kerosene solution with aqueous ferrous sulphamate, which selectively reduces the plutonium to the +3 oxidation state.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The plutonium passes into the aqueous phase.
[src:chemistry/actinide-chemistry] The uranium is stripped from the kerosene solution by back-extraction into nitric acid at a concentration of ca.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius model of reaction rates, **activation energy** is the minimum amount of energy that must be available to reactants for a chemical reaction to occur.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The activation energy (*E*a) of a reaction is measured in kilojoules per mole (kJ/mol) or kilocalories per mole (kcal/mol).
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Activation energy is the minimum energy barrier that reactant molecules must overcome to transform into products.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] A reaction occurs only if enough molecules have kinetic energy equal to or greater than this barrier, which usually requires sufficiently high temperature.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The term "activation energy" was introduced in 1889 by the Swedish scientist Svante Arrhenius.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Although less commonly used, activation energy also applies to nuclear reactions and various other physical phenomena.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The Arrhenius equation gives the quantitative basis of the relationship between the activation energy and the rate at which a reaction proceeds.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] where *A* is the pre-exponential factor for the reaction, *R* is the universal gas constant, *T* is the absolute temperature (usually in kelvins), and *k* is the reaction rate coefficient.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Even without knowing *A*, *E*a can be evaluated from the variation in reaction rate coefficients as a function of temperature (within the validity of the Arrhenius equation).
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] At a more advanced level, the net Arrhenius activation energy term from the Arrhenius equation is best regarded as an experimentally determined parameter that indicates the sensitivity of the reaction rate to temperature.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] There are two objections to associating this activation energy with the threshold barrier for an elementary reaction.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] First, it is often unclear as to whether or not reaction does proceed in one step; threshold barriers that are averaged out over all elementary steps have little theoretical value.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] A substance that modifies the transition state to lower the activation energy is termed a catalyst; a catalyst composed only of protein and (if applicable) small molecule cofactors is termed an enzyme.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] A catalyst increases the rate of reaction without being consumed in the reaction.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In addition, the catalyst lowers the activation energy, but it does not change the energies of the original reactants or products, and so does not change equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Rather, the reactant energy and the product energy remain the same and only the *activation energy* is altered (lowered).
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] A catalyst is able to reduce the activation energy by forming a transition state in a more favorable manner.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Catalysts, by nature, create a more "comfortable" fit for the substrate of a reaction to progress to a transition state.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] This is possible due to a release of energy that occurs when the substrate binds to the active site of a catalyst.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Upon binding to a catalyst, substrates partake in numerous stabilizing forces while within the active site (e.g. hydrogen bonding or van der Waals forces).
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Specific and favorable bonding occurs within the active site until the substrate forms to become the high-energy transition state.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Forming the transition state is more favorable with the catalyst because the favorable stabilizing interactions within the active site *release* energy.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] A chemical reaction is able to manufacture a high-energy transition state molecule more readily when there is a stabilizing fit within the active site of a catalyst.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The binding energy of a reaction is this energy released when favorable interactions between substrate and catalyst occur.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The binding energy released assists in achieving the unstable transition state.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Reactions without catalysts need a higher input of energy to achieve the transition state.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Non-catalyzed reactions do not have free energy available from active site stabilizing interactions, such as catalytic enzyme reactions.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius equation, the term activation energy (*E*a) is used to describe the energy required to reach the transition state, and the exponential relationship *k* = *A* exp(−*E*a/*RT*) holds.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In transition state theory, a more sophisticated model of the relationship between reaction rates and the transition state, a superficially similar mathematical relationship, the Eyring equation, is used to describe the rate constant of a reaction: *k* = (*k*B*T* / *h*) exp(−Δ*G*‡ / *RT*).
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] However, instead of modeling the temperature dependence of reaction rate phenomenologically, the Eyring equation models individual elementary steps of a reaction.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Thus, for a multistep process, there is no straightforward relationship between the two models.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Nevertheless, the functional forms of the Arrhenius and Eyring equations are similar, and for a one-step process, simple and chemically meaningful correspondences can be drawn between Arrhenius and Eyring parameters.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Instead of also using *E*a, the Eyring equation uses the concept of Gibbs energy and the symbol Δ*G*‡ to denote the Gibbs energy of activation to achieve the transition state.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In the equation, *k*B and *h* are the Boltzmann and Planck constants, respectively.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Although the equations look similar, the Gibbs energy contains an entropic term in addition to the enthalpic one.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In the Arrhenius equation, this entropic term is accounted for by the pre-exponential factor *A*.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] More specifically, we can write the Gibbs free energy of activation in terms of enthalpy and entropy of activation: Δ*G*‡ = Δ*H*‡ − *T* Δ*S*‡.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Then, for a unimolecular, one-step reaction, the *approximate* relationships *E*a = Δ*H*‡ + *RT* and *A* = (*k*B*T*/*h*) exp(1 + Δ*S*‡/*R*) hold.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Note, however, that in Arrhenius theory proper, *A* is temperature independent, while here, there is a linear dependence on *T*.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] For a one-step unimolecular process whose half-life at room temperature is about 2 hours, Δ*G*‡ is approximately 23 kcal/mol.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] This is also the roughly the magnitude of *E*a for a reaction that proceeds over several hours at room temperature.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Due to the relatively small magnitude of *T*Δ*S*‡ and *RT* at ordinary temperatures for most reactions, in sloppy discourse, *E*a, Δ*G*‡, and Δ*H*‡ are often conflated and all referred to as the "activation energy".
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The enthalpy, entropy and Gibbs energy of activation are more correctly written as Δ‡*H*o, Δ‡*S*o and Δ‡*G*o respectively, where the o indicates a quantity evaluated between standard states.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] However, some authors omit the o in order to simplify the notation.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The total free energy change of a reaction is independent of the activation energy however.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Physical and chemical reactions can be either exergonic or endergonic, but the activation energy is not related to the spontaneity of a reaction.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The overall reaction energy change is not altered by the activation energy.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In some cases, rates of reaction *decrease* with increasing temperature.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] When following an approximately exponential relationship so the rate constant can still be fit to an Arrhenius expression, this results in a negative value of *E*a.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Elementary reactions exhibiting negative activation energies are typically barrierless reactions, in which the reaction proceeding relies on the capture of the molecules in a potential well.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Such a situation no longer leads itself to direct interpretations as the height of a potential barrier.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Some multistep reactions can also have apparent negative activation energies.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] For example, the overall rate constant k for a two-step reaction A ⇌ B, B → C is given by k = k2K1, where k2 is the rate constant of the rate-limiting slow second step and K1 is the equilibrium constant of the rapid first step.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] In some reactions, K1 decreases with temperature more rapidly than k2 increases, so that k actually decreases with temperature corresponding to a negative observed activation energy.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] An example is the oxidation of nitric oxide which is a termolecular reaction ${\ce {2 NO + O2 -> 2 NO2}}$ .
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] Certain cationic polymerization reactions have negative activation energies so that the rate decreases with temperature.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] For chain-growth polymerization, the overall activation energy is $\textstyle E=E_{i}+E_{p}-E_{t}$ , where i, p and t refer respectively to initiation, propagation and termination steps.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The propagation step normally has a very small activation energy, so that the overall value is negative if the activation energy for termination is larger than that for initiation.
[src:chemistry/activation-energy] The normal range of overall activation energies for cationic polymerization varies from 40 to 60 kJ/mol.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In the scope of its subject, chemistry occupies an intermediate position between physics and biology.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] It is sometimes called the central science because it provides a foundation for understanding both basic and applied scientific disciplines at a fundamental level.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemistry has existed under various names since ancient times.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] It has evolved, and now chemistry encompasses various areas of specialisation, or subdisciplines, that continue to increase in number and interrelate to create further interdisciplinary fields of study.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The applications of various fields of chemistry are used frequently for economic purposes in the chemical industry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The word *chemistry* comes from a modification during the Renaissance of the word *alchemy,* which referred to an earlier set of practices that encompassed elements of chemistry, metallurgy, philosophy, astrology, astronomy, mysticism, and medicine.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Alchemy is often associated with the quest to turn lead or other base metals into gold, though alchemists were also interested in many of the questions of modern chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The modern word *alchemy* in turn is derived from the Arabic word *al-kīmīā* (الكیمیاء).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] This may have Egyptian origins since *al-kīmīā* is derived from the Ancient Greek χημία, which is in turn derived from the word *Kemet*, which is the ancient name of Egypt in the Egyptian language.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Alternately, *al-kīmīā* may derive from χημεία 'cast together'.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The current model of atomic structure is the quantum mechanical model.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Traditional chemistry starts with the study of elementary particles, atoms, molecules, substances, metals, crystals and other aggregates of matter.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Matter can be studied in solid, liquid, gas and plasma states, in isolation or in combination.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The interactions, reactions and transformations that are studied in chemistry are usually the result of interactions between atoms, leading to rearrangements of the chemical bonds which hold atoms together.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Such behaviors are studied in a chemistry laboratory.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The chemistry laboratory stereotypically uses various forms of laboratory glassware.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] However glassware is not central to chemistry, and a great deal of experimental (as well as applied/industrial) chemistry is done without it.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A chemical reaction is a transformation of some substances into one or more different substances.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The basis of such a chemical transformation is the rearrangement of electrons in the chemical bonds between atoms.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] It can be symbolically depicted through a chemical equation, which usually involves atoms as subjects.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The number of atoms on the left and the right in the equation for a chemical transformation is equal.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] (When the number of atoms on either side is unequal, the transformation is referred to as a nuclear reaction or radioactive decay.) The type of chemical reactions a substance may undergo and the energy changes that may accompany it are constrained by certain basic rules, known as chemical laws.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Energy and entropy considerations are invariably important in almost all chemical studies.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemical substances are classified in terms of their structure, phase, as well as their chemical compositions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] They can be analyzed using the tools of chemical analysis, e.g. spectroscopy and chromatography.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Scientists engaged in chemical research are known as chemists.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Most chemists specialize in one or more sub-disciplines.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In chemistry, matter is defined as anything that has rest mass and volume (it takes up space) and is made up of particles.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The particles that make up matter have rest mass as well – not all particles have rest mass, such as the photon.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Matter can be a pure chemical substance or a mixture of substances.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The atom is the basic unit of chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] It consists of a dense core called the atomic nucleus surrounded by a space occupied by an electron cloud.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The nucleus is made up of positively charged protons and uncharged neutrons (together called nucleons), while the electron cloud consists of negatively charged electrons which orbit the nucleus.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In a neutral atom, the negatively charged electrons balance out the positive charge of the protons.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The nucleus is dense; the mass of a nucleon is approximately 1,836 times that of an electron, yet the radius of an atom is about 10,000 times that of its nucleus.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The atom is also the smallest entity that can be envisaged to retain the chemical properties of the element, such as electronegativity, ionization potential, preferred oxidation state(s), coordination number, and preferred types of bonds to form (e.g., metallic, ionic, covalent).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A chemical element is a pure substance which is composed of a single type of atom, characterized by its particular number of protons in the nuclei of its atoms, known as the atomic number and represented by the symbol *Z*.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The mass number is the sum of the number of protons and neutrons in a nucleus.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Although all the nuclei of all atoms belonging to one element will have the same atomic number, they may not necessarily have the same mass number; atoms of an element which have different mass numbers are known as isotopes.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] For example, all atoms with 6 protons in their nuclei are atoms of the chemical element carbon, but atoms of carbon may have mass numbers of 12 or 13.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The standard presentation of the chemical elements is in the periodic table, which orders elements by atomic number.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The periodic table is arranged in groups, or columns, and periods, or rows.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The periodic table is useful in identifying periodic trends.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A *compound* is a pure chemical substance composed of more than one element.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The properties of a compound bear little similarity to those of its elements.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The standard nomenclature of compounds is set by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Organic compounds are named according to the organic nomenclature system.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The names for inorganic compounds are created according to the inorganic nomenclature system.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When a compound has more than one component, then they are divided into two classes, the electropositive and the electronegative components.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In addition the Chemical Abstracts Service (CAS) has devised a method to index chemical substances.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In this scheme each chemical substance is identifiable by a number known as its CAS registry number.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A *molecule* is the smallest indivisible portion of a pure chemical substance that has its unique set of chemical properties, that is, its potential to undergo a certain set of chemical reactions with other substances.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] However, this definition only works well for substances that are composed of molecules, which is not true of many substances (see below).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Molecules are typically a set of atoms bound together by covalent bonds, such that the structure is electrically neutral and all valence electrons are paired with other electrons either in bonds or in lone pairs.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Thus, molecules exist as electrically neutral units, unlike ions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When this rule is broken, giving the "molecule" a charge, the result is sometimes named a molecular ion or a polyatomic ion.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] However, the discrete and separate nature of the molecular concept usually requires that molecular ions be present only in well-separated form, such as a directed beam in a vacuum in a mass spectrometer.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Charged polyatomic collections residing in solids (for example, common sulfate or nitrate ions) are generally not considered "molecules" in chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Some molecules contain one or more unpaired electrons, creating radicals.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Most radicals are comparatively reactive, but some, such as nitric oxide (NO) can be stable.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The "inert" or noble gas elements (helium, neon, argon, krypton, xenon and radon) are composed of lone atoms as their smallest discrete unit, but the other isolated chemical elements consist of either molecules or networks of atoms bonded to each other in some way.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Identifiable molecules compose familiar substances such as water, air, and many organic compounds like alcohol, sugar, gasoline, and the various pharmaceuticals.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] However, not all substances or chemical compounds consist of discrete molecules, and indeed most of the solid substances that make up the solid crust, mantle, and core of the Earth are chemical compounds without molecules.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] These other types of substances, such as ionic compounds and network solids, are organized in such a way as to lack the existence of identifiable molecules *per se*.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Instead, these substances are discussed in terms of formula units or unit cells as the smallest repeating structure within the substance.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Examples of such substances are mineral salts (such as table salt), solids like carbon and diamond, metals, and familiar silica and silicate minerals such as quartz and granite.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] One of the main characteristics of a molecule is its geometry often called its structure.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] While the structure of diatomic, triatomic or tetra-atomic molecules may be trivial, (linear, angular pyramidal etc.) the structure of polyatomic molecules, that are constituted of more than six atoms (of several elements) can be crucial for its chemical nature.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A chemical substance is a kind of matter with a definite composition and set of properties.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A collection of substances is called a mixture.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Examples of mixtures are air and alloys.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The mole is a unit of measurement that denotes an amount of substance (also called chemical amount).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] One mole is defined to contain exactly 6.02214076×1023 particles (atoms, molecules, ions, or electrons), where the number of particles per mole is known as the Avogadro constant.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Molar concentration is the amount of a particular substance per volume of solution, and is commonly reported in mol/dm3.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In addition to the specific chemical properties that distinguish different chemical classifications, chemicals can exist in several phases.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] For the most part, the chemical classifications are independent of these bulk phase classifications; however, some more exotic phases are incompatible with certain chemical properties.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A *phase* is a set of states of a chemical system that have similar bulk structural properties, over a range of conditions, such as pressure or temperature.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Physical properties, such as density and refractive index tend to fall within values characteristic of the phase.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The phase of matter is defined by the *phase transition*, which is when energy put into or taken out of the system goes into rearranging the structure of the system, instead of changing the bulk conditions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Sometimes the distinction between phases can be continuous instead of having a discrete boundary; in this case the matter is considered to be in a supercritical state.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When three states meet based on the conditions, it is known as a triple point and since this is invariant, it is a convenient way to define a set of conditions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The most familiar examples of phases are solids, liquids, and gases.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Many substances exhibit multiple solid phases.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] For example, there are three phases of solid iron (alpha, gamma, and delta) that vary based on temperature and pressure.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A principal difference between solid phases is the crystal structure, or arrangement, of the atoms.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Another phase commonly encountered in the study of chemistry is the *aqueous* phase, which is the state of substances dissolved in aqueous solution (that is, in water).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Less familiar phases include plasmas, Bose–Einstein condensates and fermionic condensates and the paramagnetic and ferromagnetic phases of magnetic materials.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] While most familiar phases deal with three-dimensional systems, it is also possible to define analogs in two-dimensional systems, which has received attention for its relevance to systems in biology.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Atoms sticking together in molecules or crystals are said to be bonded with one another.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A chemical bond may be visualized as the multipole balance between the positive charges in the nuclei and the negative charges oscillating about them.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] More than simple attraction and repulsion, the energies and distributions characterize the availability of an electron to bond to another atom.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The chemical bond can be a covalent bond, an ionic bond, a hydrogen bond or just because of Van der Waals force.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Each of these kinds of bonds is ascribed to some potential.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] These potentials create the interactions which hold atoms together in molecules or crystals.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In many simple compounds, valence bond theory, the Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion model (VSEPR), and the concept of oxidation number can be used to explain molecular structure and composition.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] An ionic bond is formed when a metal loses one or more of its electrons, becoming a positively charged cation, and the electrons are then gained by the non-metal atom, becoming a negatively charged anion.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The two oppositely charged ions attract one another, and the ionic bond is the electrostatic force of attraction between them.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] For example, sodium (Na), a metal, loses one electron to become an Na+ cation while chlorine (Cl), a non-metal, gains this electron to become Cl−.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The ions are held together due to electrostatic attraction, and that compound sodium chloride (NaCl), or common table salt, is formed.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In a covalent bond, one or more pairs of valence electrons are shared by two atoms: the resulting electrically neutral group of bonded atoms is termed a molecule.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Atoms will share valence electrons in such a way as to create a noble gas electron configuration (eight electrons in their outermost shell) for each atom.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Atoms that tend to combine in such a way that they each have eight electrons in their valence shell are said to follow the octet rule.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Similarly, theories from classical physics can be used to predict many ionic structures.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] With more complicated compounds, such as metal complexes, valence bond theory is less applicable and alternative approaches, such as the molecular orbital theory, are generally used.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In the context of chemistry, energy is an attribute of a substance as a consequence of its atomic, molecular or aggregate structure.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Since a chemical transformation is accompanied by a change in one or more of these kinds of structures, it is invariably accompanied by an increase or decrease of energy of the substances involved.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Some energy is transferred between the surroundings and the reactants of the reaction in the form of heat or light; thus the products of a reaction may have more or less energy than the reactants.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A reaction is said to be exergonic if the final state is lower on the energy scale than the initial state; in the case of endergonic reactions the situation is the reverse.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A reaction is said to be exothermic if the reaction releases heat to the surroundings; in the case of endothermic reactions, the reaction absorbs heat from the surroundings.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemical reactions are invariably not possible unless the reactants surmount an energy barrier known as the activation energy.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The *speed* of a chemical reaction (at given temperature T) is related to the activation energy E, by the Boltzmann's population factor $e^{-E/kT}$ – that is the probability of a molecule to have energy greater than or equal to E at the given temperature T.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] This exponential dependence of a reaction rate on temperature is known as the Arrhenius equation.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The activation energy necessary for a chemical reaction to occur can be in the form of heat, light, electricity or mechanical force in the form of ultrasound.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A related concept free energy, which also incorporates entropy considerations, is a very useful means for predicting the feasibility of a reaction and determining the state of equilibrium of a chemical reaction, in chemical thermodynamics.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A reaction is feasible only if the total change in the Gibbs free energy is negative, $\Delta G\leq 0\,$ ; if it is equal to zero the chemical reaction is said to be at equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] There exist only limited possible states of energy for electrons, atoms and molecules.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] These are determined by the rules of quantum mechanics, which require quantization of energy of a bound system.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The atoms/molecules in a higher energy state are said to be excited.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The molecules/atoms of substance in an excited energy state are often much more reactive; that is, more amenable to chemical reactions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The phase of a substance is invariably determined by its energy and the energy of its surroundings.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When the intermolecular forces of a substance are such that the energy of the surroundings is not sufficient to overcome them, it occurs in a more ordered phase like liquid or solid as is the case with water (H2O); a liquid at room temperature because its molecules are bound by hydrogen bonds.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Whereas hydrogen sulfide (H2S) is a gas at room temperature and standard pressure, as its molecules are bound by weaker dipole–dipole interactions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The transfer of energy from one chemical substance to another depends on the *size* of energy quanta emitted from one substance.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] However, heat energy is often transferred more easily from almost any substance to another because the phonons responsible for vibrational and rotational energy levels in a substance have much less energy than photons invoked for the electronic energy transfer.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Thus, because vibrational and rotational energy levels are more closely spaced than electronic energy levels, heat is more easily transferred between substances relative to light or other forms of electronic energy.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] For example, ultraviolet electromagnetic radiation is not transferred with as much efficacy from one substance to another as thermal or electrical energy.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The existence of characteristic energy levels for different chemical substances is useful for their identification by the analysis of spectral lines.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Different kinds of spectra are often used in chemical spectroscopy, e.g.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Spectroscopy is also used to identify the composition of remote objects – like stars and distant galaxies – by analyzing their radiation spectra.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The term chemical energy is often used to indicate the potential of a chemical substance to undergo a transformation through a chemical reaction or to transform other chemical substances.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When a chemical substance is transformed as a result of its interaction with another substance or with energy, a chemical reaction is said to have occurred.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A *chemical reaction* is therefore a concept related to the "reaction" of a substance when it comes in close contact with another, whether as a mixture or a solution; exposure to some form of energy, or both.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] It results in some energy exchange between the constituents of the reaction as well as with the system environment, which may be designed vessels—often laboratory glassware.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemical reactions can result in the formation or dissociation of molecules, that is, molecules breaking apart to form two or more molecules or rearrangement of atoms within or across molecules.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemical reactions usually involve the making or breaking of chemical bonds.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Oxidation, reduction, dissociation, acid–base neutralization and molecular rearrangement are some examples of common chemical reactions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A chemical reaction can be symbolically depicted through a chemical equation.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] While in a non-nuclear chemical reaction the number and kind of atoms on both sides of the equation are equal, for a nuclear reaction this holds true only for the nuclear particles viz. protons and neutrons.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The sequence of steps in which the reorganization of chemical bonds may be taking place in the course of a chemical reaction is called its mechanism.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A chemical reaction can be envisioned to take place in a number of steps, each of which may have a different speed.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Many reaction intermediates with variable stability can thus be envisaged during the course of a reaction.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Reaction mechanisms are proposed to explain the kinetics and the relative product mix of a reaction.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Many physical chemists specialize in exploring and proposing the mechanisms of various chemical reactions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Several empirical rules, like the Woodward–Hoffmann rules often come in handy while proposing a mechanism for a chemical reaction.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] According to the IUPAC gold book, a chemical reaction is "a process that results in the interconversion of chemical species." Accordingly, a chemical reaction may be an elementary reaction or a stepwise reaction.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] An additional caveat is made, in that this definition includes cases where the interconversion of conformers is experimentally observable.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Such detectable chemical reactions normally involve sets of molecular entities as indicated by this definition, but it is often conceptually convenient to use the term also for changes involving single molecular entities (i.e.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] An *ion* is a charged species, an atom or a molecule, that has lost or gained one or more electrons.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When an atom loses an electron and thus has more protons than electrons, the atom is a positively charged ion or cation.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] When an atom gains an electron and thus has more electrons than protons, the atom is a negatively charged ion or anion.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Cations and anions can form a crystalline lattice of neutral salts, such as the Na+ and Cl− ions forming sodium chloride, or NaCl.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Examples of polyatomic ions that do not split up during acid–base reactions are hydroxide (OH−) and phosphate (PO43−).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Plasma is composed of gaseous matter that has been completely ionized, usually through high temperature.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A substance can often be classified as an acid or a base.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] There are several different theories which explain acid–base behavior.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The simplest is Arrhenius theory, which states that an acid is a substance that produces hydronium ions when it is dissolved in water, and a base is one that produces hydroxide ions when dissolved in water.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] According to Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, acids are substances that donate a positive hydrogen ion to another substance in a chemical reaction; by extension, a base is the substance which receives that hydrogen ion.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A third common theory is Lewis acid–base theory, which is based on the formation of new chemical bonds.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Lewis theory explains that an acid is a substance which is capable of accepting a pair of electrons from another substance during the process of bond formation, while a base is a substance which can provide a pair of electrons to form a new bond.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] There are several other ways in which a substance may be classified as an acid or a base, as is evident in the history of this concept.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Acid strength is commonly measured by two methods.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] One measurement, based on the Arrhenius definition of acidity, is pH, which is a measurement of the hydronium ion concentration in a solution, as expressed on a negative logarithmic scale.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Thus, solutions that have a low pH have a high hydronium ion concentration and can be said to be more acidic.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The other measurement, based on the Brønsted–Lowry definition, is the acid dissociation constant (Ka), which measures the relative ability of a substance to act as an acid under the Brønsted–Lowry definition of an acid.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] That is, substances with a higher Ka are more likely to donate hydrogen ions in chemical reactions than those with lower Ka values.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Redox (*red*uction-*ox*idation) reactions include all chemical reactions in which atoms have their oxidation state changed by either gaining electrons (reduction) or losing electrons (oxidation).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Substances that have the ability to oxidize other substances are said to be oxidative and are known as oxidizing agents, oxidants or oxidizers.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] An oxidant removes electrons from another substance.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Similarly, substances that have the ability to reduce other substances are said to be reductive and are known as reducing agents, reductants, or reducers.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A reductant transfers electrons to another substance and is thus oxidized itself.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] And because it "donates" electrons it is also called an electron donor.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Oxidation and reduction properly refer to a change in oxidation number—the actual transfer of electrons may never occur.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Thus, oxidation is better defined as an increase in oxidation number, and reduction as a decrease in oxidation number.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A system of chemical substances at equilibrium, even though having an unchanging composition, is most often not static; molecules of the substances continue to react with one another thus giving rise to a dynamic equilibrium.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Thus the concept describes the state in which the parameters such as chemical composition remain unchanged over time.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemical reactions are governed by certain laws, which have become fundamental concepts in chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The history of chemistry spans a period from the ancient past to the present.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Since several millennia BC, civilizations were using technologies that would eventually form the basis of the various branches of chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Examples include extracting metals from ores, making pottery and glazes, fermenting beer and wine, extracting chemicals from plants for medicine and perfume, rendering fat into soap, making glass, and making alloys like bronze.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemistry was preceded by its protoscience, alchemy, which operated a non-scientific approach to understanding the constituents of matter and their interactions.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Despite being unsuccessful in explaining the nature of matter and its transformations, alchemists set the stage for modern chemistry by performing experiments and recording the results.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Robert Boyle, although skeptical of elements and convinced of alchemy, played a key part in elevating the "sacred art" as an independent, fundamental and philosophical discipline in his work *The Sceptical Chymist* (1661).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] While both alchemy and chemistry are concerned with matter and its transformations, the crucial difference was given by the scientific method that chemists employed in their work.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemistry, as a body of knowledge distinct from alchemy, became an established science with the work of Antoine Lavoisier, who developed a law of conservation of mass that demanded careful measurement and quantitative observations of chemical phenomena.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The history of chemistry afterwards is intertwined with the history of thermodynamics, especially through the work of Willard Gibbs.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The definition of chemistry has changed over time, as new discoveries and theories add to the functionality of the science.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The term "chymistry", in the view of noted scientist Robert Boyle in 1661, meant the subject of the material principles of mixed bodies.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In 1663, the chemist Christopher Glaser described "chymistry" as a scientific art, by which one learns to dissolve bodies, and draw from them the different substances on their composition, and how to unite them again, and exalt them to a higher perfection.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The 1730 definition of the word "chemistry", as used by Georg Ernst Stahl, meant the art of resolving mixed, compound, or aggregate bodies into their principles; and of composing such bodies from those principles.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In 1837, Jean-Baptiste Dumas considered the word "chemistry" to refer to the science concerned with the laws and effects of molecular forces.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] This definition further evolved until, in 1947, it came to mean the science of substances: their structure, their properties, and the reactions that change them into other substances—a characterization accepted by Linus Pauling.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] More recently, in 1998, Professor Raymond Chang broadened the definition of "chemistry" to mean the study of matter and the changes it undergoes.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Early civilizations, such as the Egyptians, Babylonians, and Indians, amassed practical knowledge concerning the arts of metallurgy, pottery and dyes, but did not develop a systematic theory.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] A basic chemical hypothesis first emerged in Classical Greece with the theory of four elements as propounded definitively by Aristotle stating that fire, air, earth and water were the fundamental elements from which everything is formed as a combination.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Greek atomism dates back to 440 BC, arising in works by philosophers such as Democritus and Epicurus.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In 50 BCE, the Roman philosopher Lucretius expanded upon the theory in his poem *De rerum natura* (On The Nature of Things).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Unlike modern concepts of science, Greek atomism was purely philosophical in nature, with little concern for empirical observations and no concern for chemical experiments.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] An early form of the idea of conservation of mass is the notion that "Nothing comes from nothing" in Ancient Greek philosophy, which can be found in Empedocles (approx.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In the Hellenistic world the art of alchemy first proliferated, mingling magic and occultism into the study of natural substances with the ultimate goal of transmuting elements into gold and discovering the elixir of eternal life.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Work, particularly the development of distillation, continued in the early Byzantine period with the most famous practitioner being the 4th century Greek-Egyptian Zosimos of Panopolis.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Alchemy continued to be developed and practised throughout the Arab world after the Muslim conquests, and from there, and from the Byzantine remnants, diffused into medieval and Renaissance Europe through Latin translations.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The Arabic works attributed to Jabir ibn Hayyan introduced a systematic classification of chemical substances, and provided instructions for deriving an inorganic compound (sal ammoniac or ammonium chloride) from organic substances (such as plants, blood, and hair) by chemical means.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Later influential Muslim philosophers, such as Abū al-Rayhān al-Bīrūnī and Avicenna disputed the theories of alchemy, particularly the theory of the transmutation of metals.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Improvements of the refining of ores and their extractions to smelt metals was widely used source of information for early chemists in the 16th century, among them Georg Agricola (1494–1555), who published his major work *De re metallica* in 1556.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] His work, describing highly developed and complex processes of mining metal ores and metal extraction, were the pinnacle of metallurgy during that time.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] His approach removed all mysticism associated with the subject, creating the practical base upon which others could and would build.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The work describes the many kinds of furnaces used to smelt ore, and stimulated interest in minerals and their composition.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Agricola has been described as the "father of metallurgy" and the founder of geology as a scientific discipline.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Under the influence of the Scientific Revolution and its new empirical methods propounded by Sir Francis Bacon and others, a group of chemists at Oxford, Robert Boyle, Robert Hooke and John Mayow began to reshape the old alchemical traditions into a scientific discipline.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Boyle in particular questioned some commonly held chemical theories and argued for chemical practitioners to be more "philosophical" and less commercially focused in *The Sceptical Chemyst*.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] He formulated Boyle's law, rejected the classical "four elements" and proposed a mechanistic alternative of atoms and chemical reactions that could be subject to rigorous experiment.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In the following decades, many important discoveries were made, such as the nature of 'air' which was discovered to be composed of many different gases.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The Scottish chemist Joseph Black and the Flemish Jan Baptist van Helmont discovered carbon dioxide, or what Black called 'fixed air' in 1754; Henry Cavendish discovered hydrogen and elucidated its properties and Joseph Priestley and, independently, Carl Wilhelm Scheele isolated pure oxygen.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The theory of phlogiston (a substance at the root of all combustion) was propounded by the German Georg Ernst Stahl in the early 18th century and was only overturned by the end of the century by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, the chemical analogue of Newton in physics.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Lavoisier did more than any other to establish the new science on proper theoretical footing, by elucidating the principle of conservation of mass and developing a new system of chemical nomenclature used to this day.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] English scientist John Dalton proposed the modern theory of atoms; that all substances are composed of indivisible 'atoms' of matter and that different atoms have varying atomic weights.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The development of the electrochemical theory of chemical combinations occurred in the early 19th century as the result of the work of two scientists in particular, Jöns Jacob Berzelius and Humphry Davy, made possible by the prior invention of the voltaic pile by Alessandro Volta.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Davy discovered nine new elements including the alkali metals by extracting them from their oxides with electric current.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] British William Prout first proposed ordering all the elements by their atomic weight as all atoms had a weight that was an exact multiple of the atomic weight of hydrogen.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Newlands devised an early table of elements, which was then developed into the modern periodic table of elements in the 1860s by Dmitri Mendeleev and independently by several other scientists including Julius Lothar Meyer.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The inert gases, later called the noble gases were discovered by William Ramsay in collaboration with Lord Rayleigh at the end of the century, thereby filling in the basic structure of the table.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Organic chemistry was developed by Justus von Liebig and others, following Friedrich Wöhler's synthesis of urea.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Other crucial 19th century advances were; an understanding of valence bonding (Edward Frankland in 1852) and the application of thermodynamics to chemistry (J.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Gibbs and Svante Arrhenius in the 1870s).
[src:chemistry/chemistry] At the turn of the twentieth century the theoretical underpinnings of chemistry were finally understood due to a series of remarkable discoveries that succeeded in probing and discovering the very nature of the internal structure of atoms.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Thomson of the University of Cambridge discovered the electron and soon after the French scientist Becquerel as well as the couple Pierre and Marie Curie investigated the phenomenon of radioactivity.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] His work on atomic structure was improved on by his students, the Danish physicist Niels Bohr, the Englishman Henry Moseley and the German Otto Hahn, who went on to father the emerging nuclear chemistry and discovered nuclear fission.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The electronic theory of chemical bonds and molecular orbitals was developed by the American scientists Linus Pauling and Gilbert N.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The year 2011 was declared by the United Nations as the International Year of Chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] As one of the United Nations' many International Year designations, it was an initiative to broaden outreach and public understanding in chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The year was chosen as the 100th anniversary of Marie Curie's receipt of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Several years later, in 2019, the UN declared the International Year of the Periodic Table.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] In the practice of chemistry, **pure chemistry** is the study of the fundamental principles of chemistry, while **applied chemistry** applies that knowledge to develop technology and solve real-world problems.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] Chemistry is typically divided into several major sub-disciplines.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] There are also several main cross-disciplinary and more specialized fields of chemistry.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The chemical industry represents an important economic activity worldwide.
[src:chemistry/chemistry] The global top 50 chemical producers in 2013 had sales of US$980.5 billion with a profit margin of 10.3%.
